</h3><p class="sc-cZMNgc hqfPHB pf-45_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">The SRA's primary role is to regulate solicitors and their firms to protect the public and ensure high professional standards. This involves:


























</p><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-bQtKYq czWvgn pf-47_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-48_ pf-text-1"><strong>Setting standards </strong>- The SRA sets educational and training standards for solicitors to ensure they are competent to practice.







</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-50_ pf-text-1"><strong>Enforcing compliance</strong> - The SRA ensures solicitors and firms comply with legal and ethical standards through rigorous monitoring and enforcement.










</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-52_ pf-text-1"><strong>Handling complaints</strong> - The SRA investigates complaints about solicitors and firms, taking disciplinary action where necessary.</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-54_ pf-text-1"><strong>Providing guidance</strong> - The SRA offers guidance on professional conduct, helping solicitors navigate complex legal and ethical issues.












</li></ul></div></div></div><div class="sc-egiyK kKHsVi pf-56_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-ilfuhL ejXpQB pf-57_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-58_ pf-heading-1-h3">Best practices for implementing SRA regulations
</h3><p class="sc-cZMNgc hqfPHB pf-60_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">To effectively implement SRA regulations, legal firms should adopt the following best practices:



























</p><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-bQtKYq czWvgn pf-62_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-63_ pf-text-1"><strong>Continuous Professional Development (CPD)</strong> - Solicitors must engage in ongoing professional development to keep their knowledge and skills current. The SRA mandates a minimum of 16 hours of CPD annually, with at least four hours devoted to ethics, professionalism, and compliance.








</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-65_ pf-text-1"><strong>Robust compliance systems </strong>- Firms should establish robust compliance systems, including regular audits, risk assessments, and internal reviews. This ensures adherence to SRA standards and identifies areas for improvement.











</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-67_ pf-text-1"><strong>Ethics training </strong>- Regular ethics training is crucial. Firms should integrate ethics into their training programmes, fostering a culture of integrity and professionalism.</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-fXEqDS gMGtOR pf-69_ pf-text-1"><strong>Transparent complaint handling</strong> - A transparent and accessible complaint handling process is vital. Firms must ensure clients can easily lodge complaints and that these are handled swiftly and fairly in accordance with SRA guidelines.
